Five years ago, I said this. 👇🏼

👋🏼 If you need me, I will be right here.. FORR EV ERR! (⚾️ Sandlot reference). Sweet girl is doing okay today. She is learning how to suck on her plug again! 👏🏻👏🏻 That is great because it means she can swallow and take a bottle eventually. .
.
Whats not so great is last night she started throwing up a again so she got the throw up tube back in her right nostril 👃🏼. A few hours after that, she started having blood in her stool. They decided to start treating her for NEC again. Holding her feeds, and starting her on antibiotics. .
.
Her lungs still sounds great and she is breathing like a champ. Just gotta keep on keepin on. .

Five years ago, I said this.👇🏼 
.
This girl is killin it today! 🙌🏼 She got the arterial line (IV) out of her left inner thigh, and she also got her right chest tube out! This girl has ZERO CHEST TUBES, as of right now! 👏🏻👏🏻 The chest tube still had some drainage but they are hoping her body can absorb the fluid naturally rather than having it drain out of the chest tube. Her x rays are looking great. They don’t see any perforations or openings from her bowel. With NEC they are worried about those openings because if your bowel is leaking then she would become septic and that is fatal. So, to reiterate, her belly looks great on the x rays. They are still holding her feeds and giving her antibiotics to treat for NEC, but they think they caught it in time. Her blood pressure is great, her heart rate is great, her lungs sound perfect and they are slowly turning down her high flow (air sent into her nostrils to remind her to breathe). She is comfortable and relaxed and she doesn’t look like she is struggling to breathe at all..They are still weening her off morphine and her withdrawals are causing her to hiccup, sneeze, and have the jitters. 😞 BUT even with all those things happening, she still manages to give us a smile from time to time. So proud of my baby girl! Yay for good news!

If people only understood the internal battle that goes on in a mothers head and heart when she is burying her child. 
.
Holding it together for others.. crumbling the second they leave. Comforting friends and family around me as they sob because THEY not only lost Everly, but they are suffering because they love us and WE are suffering because we lost Everly. And around and around. There is no way to describe it, and I don’t wish it on anyone. A few weeks after losing Everly, I was asked to write an article for @lovewhatmatters blog. Most of the feedback was amazing and supportive, but A LOT of it was judgmental. People saying that it was “unsettling” and “eerie” that we would smile at her funeral. I felt shamed for feeling all my feelings while burying my daughter. 
.
December 15th, 2017, I said this. 👇🏼 
Tonight we had a viewing for our Sweet Everly girl. We feel so blessed to know that #familiesareforever.
.
.
Also, if you are wondering how we are doing. We are holding up. When the last person left the room, I broke down and bawled my eyes out. I have a feeling that I will continue to “keep it together” until after the funeral. Ask me next week how I am doing and I will probably be a mess.

On December 30th, 2017, I said this. 👇🏼
.
 I BEGGED my doctors to allow my friend (and photographer), Emily,  into the delivery room. C sections are done in sterile operating rooms, so besides the staff and the baby daddy, no one else is allowed to be in there. The doctors repeatedly told me that Emily wasn’t allowed in the OR (which makes sense, they are just trying to keep the baby and mama safe). Feeling so defeated I started to tear up. 😢 I looked at the anesthesiologist and said, “I don’t know how long I am going to have my daughter, these pictures mean everything to me...”. 🙏🏼 The anesthesiologist (who looked pretty annoyed at this point 🙄😒) turned to Emily and said, “You have to put on scrubs and you have to wear a hair net. I will tell you where to stand and you aren’t allowed to move from that spot.”... Point of the story, I am SOOOO happy Emily was there to capture those precious moments. I will cherish them forever and I feel so blessed to have them to look back on. #persistance #paysoff 🤭😊
.
.
Also, can I just say that it is great having besties that are amazing photographers?! @edevenney and her hubby, @cdevenneypresets, are amazing! 📷 I wanted to include some photos of Cory and Emily visiting Everly when she got moved to the third floor. ❤️ .

Everly passed away December 9th, 2017. Let me tell you… January 2018 was absolute torture. How dare the world just carry on. 🤷🏼‍♀️
This is what I said about going to a jazz game a few weeks after Everly passed away. 👇🏼 
.
This account is essentially my new journal. Especially since Everly passed away & there are no new updates on her, the only thing I can really do with this account is share how we are doing without her.
.
So here it is.. the good, the bad and the ugly. I know within my heart that Everly wants us to be happy. I know that she wouldn’t want me to stay in bed and cry all day. I know that she wants me to be strong. If only I were perfect.. 😏 Most days it’s almost impossible for me to get out of bed. I, of course, always find the motivation to get up and his name is Urban. 😊
So, tonight we were given Utah Jazz tickets from a dear friend and neighbor (remember how I have the best neighborhood ever?!) and they were too good to not use! We got a VIP tour of the stadium, ate yummy nachos followed by dip n dots, & sat in a suite! It has been FOREVER since we have done something fun like this. It felt great getting out & being “normal” for a minute. 💕Tonight we were just a cute couple in love & enjoying a basketball game. We weren’t sad, grieving, parents who just lost their baby girl..
.
BUT.. As I sit here and think about our night & how much fun we had, I can’t help but have tears in my eyes because of guilt. Guilt that I enjoyed myself. Guilt that I am trying to “move on” and trying to have my “normal” life again. Like I said before, I know she doesn’t want me to be sad. I just think I will have to keep pushing myself to be ME again. I have heard from other people who have been in my shoes that “it doesn’t get easier, you just learn to deal with it...” 😢How daunting.. but also very appropriate. .
Anyways, those are my thoughts. Any advice on things I can do to get motivated again? Books to read? Ted talks I need to listen to? I am all ears.. I need some of those things to do while I lay in bed for the next few days ✌🏼. 😑 Just kidding.. but seriously.

I WOULD LOVE TO HEAR YOUR THOUGHTS. TW 🚨 5 years ago, I said this..

“The other day Drew and I were talking about how we are getting older. Especially in the last year, we feel like we have aged sooo much! -thank you stress!- 👵🏻 .
I told him that “I am excited to get older”... and he looked at me puzzled and said “um, what?!”
I told him that I couldn’t wait to get older and enjoy everything this life has to offer, but then pass away so I can be with Everly again.
I guess when you suffer the loss of a child, you no longer fear death.. I can’t speak for everyone who has lost a child, but that’s how it is for me. 👼🏼”
.
I would love to hear your thoughts. I obviously want to be here. I need to be here for my boys. But if I died tomorrow, I’m pretty sure all of you would think, “oh she is with her Everly now.” (Or something along those lines.)
.
What are your thoughts!?

My advice. Don’t take the first “no”. Ask questions. Find out the “why’s”. And go from there. 
This is what I wrote a few years ago about the experience. 👇🏼 
.
I BEGGED my doctors to allow my friend (and photographer), Emily, into the delivery room. C sections are done in sterile operating rooms, so besides the staff and the baby daddy, no one else is allowed to be in there…? The anesthesiologist repeatedly told me that Emily wasn’t allowed in the OR (which makes sense, they are just trying to keep the baby and mama safe). Feeling so defeated I started to tear up. 😢 I looked at the anesthesiologist and said, “I don’t know how long I am going to have my daughter, these pictures mean everything to me...”. 🙏🏼 The anesthesiologist (who looked pretty annoyed at this point 🙄😒) turned to Emily and said, “You have to put on scrubs and you have to wear a hair net. I will tell you where to stand and you aren’t allowed to move from that spot.”... Point of the story, I am SOOOO happy Emily was there to capture those precious moments. I will cherish them forever and I feel so blessed to have them to look back on..
.
Do you have experience with this same situation? Tell me your thoughts.

Everyone’s grief journey is going to look so different. All of these moments happened within the first month or so of losing Everly. 
We lost her Dec 9th… we went to a New Year’s Eve gathering with our best friends that year. It felt weird, but it was necessary. You think that after losing a child, you will “stay in bed for the rest of your life because you couldn’t handle it..” no one wants to talk about how awkward it is to move forward. To keep breathing. To put one foot in front of the other. But you have to. Are you ever going stand up from your bed and go pee? Then you have to get out of bed. Those are the first steps.. it’s terrible. It’s the worst pain you will ever feel, but you wake up and you realize it’s not a dream and your heart is beating and theirs isn’t.. and you stand up to go pee. 🤷🏼‍♀️
Move forward. Not on… and honor them by living.

Even though I am constantly counting my little ducklings and missing our Everly girl, I am so extremely grateful for the life I have with my boys. I’m honoring Everly by choosing to be happy.

Meet Everly Jo Ostler. She was born this morning, Nov. 6th 2017 at 8:59 AM. Weighing 6 lbs 2 oz and 19 inches long. The C Section went well and mama is feeling great. 👍🏼 Everly was stabilized within an hour and ready to be transported to Primary Children’s Hospital. Since then, Drew has been able to spend a lot of time with her at Primary’s, while I recovered in labor and delivery just a building away (connected by a sky bridge). .
.
An update on her health and the game plan for the next few days... Right now Everly’s heart is overcompensating for her defects. They are going to monitor how she does for the next day or two, rather than taking her directly into surgery. Wednesday morning a team of 10 or 12 cardiologist will have a meeting to discuss her first surgery and what exactly they have to do. That way they will ALL decide the best route to take and we will have a better idea of when her first surgery will be. (Probably Thursday). Everly has been breathing on her own since she was born which tells us just how strong she is. 💪🏼 She is happy, calm, content, and so snuggly. 💕
.
.
We feel incredibly blessed to live so close to this amazing hospital with its amazing staff. We feel yours prayers. We feel your support. We feel so much peace. Thank you from the bottom of our hearts! .
.

As I stated yesterday, Everly had a few lines that weren’t placed accurately. This meant that when they gave her nutrition and/or medicine, it wasn’t landing in her body the exact place they wanted it to. This morning she had a procedure where they placed a new line in the back of her leg. For this procedure they sedated her A LOT, for pain and comfort purposes, and laid her on her side. The line was placed accurately through her leg and we are hoping that will help her turn a corner (or two) the next few days. They also took out the port that was going down her neck. She did okay but she did not like when the nurse was taking the tape off. It reminded me that she is awake and aware of pain. I wish I could do all this for her. She is amazing. .
.
Small victories!! She is peeing soooo much better! Baby girl just wanted to pee on her OWN. DANG. TIME, people! Also, her blood pressure is finally starting to become level! 👏🏻👏🏻 This is awesome because it means less blood pressure medicine and more medicine that will benefit the rest of her body. Keep it up little girl! We are so proud of you. Seriously, rock star status! 🤘🏼

Bare with me. This is long
.
Everly has had a rocky day. It started out amazing. They took her chest tube out (the chest tube was draining fluid from around her heart) and they took her breathing tube out. We were so excited and we felt like we were taking a few steps forward. After they took the breathing tube out her heart rate sky rocketed. They want her heart rate to be around 140 and she stayed at about 180 for a 4 hrs
.
Also, during that time, she would almost “forget” to breathe. She would open her mouth really big (swipe right) and then she would gasp for air. They couldn’t figure out why she was doing that but they told us it was probably because her muscles had to get used to breathing on her own. .
Drew and I knew something was wrong and we kept pressing the nurses & doctors. Finally one of the fellows decided to intubate her again. Although this is a step back, we were so relieved. I hope and pray none of you have to watch your child suffocate and gasp for air. I can’t describe how awful that was. .
Also, they noticed some swelling on her belly. They drew blood and we will find out in a day or two if she is septic (has some type of infection). This would explain the breathing problems and heart rate problems, BUT they aren’t convinced that’s what’s going on. .
Her surgeon is kindof on standby. He told us that if she isn’t septic then she could be getting too much blood flow from the BT Shunt they placed on Thursday. To reiterate, if she does NOT have an infection, it could be that her BT Shunt is doing TOO GOOD of a job. If this is the case, she will need to go back into surgery and they will tie off the pulmonary artery to STOP some of that blood flow. .
Are y’all confused yet? Because I totally am. As of right now Everly is sedated, intubated, and comfortable. I don’t care if intubation is a step back. She if comfortable again and maybe her body needs another few days to heal from her surgery. It has been a LONG day full of ups and down. Everly isn’t out of the woods yet and she still needs your prayers. Thank you for caring about our baby girl.  #1weeknew #1weekold #chd #chdawareness #congenitalheartdefect #heartwarrior #zipperclub

Dec 7th, 2017 I wrote this 👇🏼 

3rd floor status.. The room we are in now feels like a hotel suite. It’s massive. It has its own bathroom with a shower, a couch that folds into a bed, and a lot more privacy. So far we are loving it. Everly’s nurse is right outside and still comes in to check her vitals and update her medications if needed. Today we are having so much fun! For the first time, @andrewostler and I are alone with both our kiddos at the same time. For the first time in over a month, I don’t feel like my heart is being ripped in half by wanting to spend time with both my babies. Urban is getting spoiled by everyone here, with an endless supply of toys and snacks. We are so happy. ♥️ Yay for a bigger room, with less medicine! 🙌🏼
“Oh hey, guys! I got my stitches out today! Look how pretty my incision is looking.. and also, look how cute my face is! 💁🏼‍♀️” - Everly
Who’s with me? 🙋🏼‍♀️😵‍💫

What’s new with Everly today? A lot of things! First things first... (she the realest🎧🎵). Anyways 😂 she is finally able to eat again! She is on 1 mls an hour of a really low fat formula called Vivonex. Vivonex is for babies with extreme GI (Gastrointestinal Tract) issues. That pretty much means her tummy is sooo sensitive from her NEC and Chylo that they are trying to give her something that will be easy for her to digest. We will cross our fingers that she handles it okay because it’s really their only option. Even breast milk is too much for her tummy to handle. 🥛 🐄 
Also, her hematocrit levels were really low which means.... I have no idea. 🤷🏼‍♀️🤦🏼‍♀️ Something about her red blood cells being low compared to the rest of her blood. They want her hematocrit levels to be in the 40s, and on her last blood draw this morning, her levels were at 31. All they do to fix this is give her a small blood transfusion to help give her blood the “little boost” it needs. Thank you modern medicine! 
If any of you are in the medical field, please feel free to poke fun of me and my translations of medical terms. The truth is, I have no idea what most of these medical terms are.. even if they explain something to me 10 times, I still will google certain things because I can’t keep it all straight! 🤯
.
So now the plan is to go slow with her feeds and make sure her belly can tolerate them. This itty bitty thing is weighing in at a whopping 6.6 lbs. She’s gotta step her game up and gain some elle bees so she can get home by Christmas! 🎅🏻🎄⛄️🦄

Posting that picture, announcing her death, was the hardest moment of my life. I was mourning her, and I was mourning for all of you who had watched her journey and who was rooting for her. 
Even now, I am sorry to all of you, for losing her. For mourning her. I’m sorry you guys felt that.. because I know how much you love her. Grief is wild. 
.
Fact: the backdrop of that announcement, was the sink from Everly’s room. I was sitting right there with her body when I pressed “share”, and I mourned for myself, for my husband, for my mom and entire family, for all of you. 
.
I love you all. And thank you for loving her so much that you mourned her.
